Prior to this year, my neighbour’s main concern was bullying. Being bullied both in school and on the way to school, it made me feel extremely insecure, unsure of myself and very isolated.
It resulted in me hiding in the bathroom for the first half hour I reached home, feeling broken by the day’s events. As I was unable to make new friends, the friendship group I had always had deteriorated, making me feel even more isolated and untouchable.
With my specific scenario, I had numerous speeches, visits and gut wrenching plans to make my life worth living for.
Thank God, some adults succeeded in introducing me to Tikkun, and it has been the best thing that could have ever happened to me. Building my confidence in public speaking has opened my eyes to life’s opportunities.
I swear, the feeling of fighting alongside women whom I highly admire, whom I respect and admire with all my heart, has taught me respect and courage. It makes me feel empowered, strong, wise, ready to have my say, and feel tied to something greater than myself and most importantly save lives. Unfortunately, the only way Tikkun has the power to free the world is by having more support through donations and fundraising done either nationally or internationally.
